# Enhanced API Rules Filtering for Complex Relations #6590 - GitHub
created: 2025-03-13, last updated: 2026-04-17, [Read more](https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/discussions/6590)

Sorry disregard the above comment.
I've created a test setup with the 2 different auth collections similar to your in order to attempt to reproduce the error and indeed the rule will not work with the current back-relation resolver because we currently don't apply the `nullifyMisingField` condition for the back-relation field reference.
I've added a task in the roadmap to think a little more on it for the next release but as a workaround you can perform the join manually using the `@collection.*` field, for example your rule should be equivalent to:
```
@request.auth.collectionName = 'admins' ||
(
@request.auth.collectionName = 'users' &&
@collection.courseRegistrations.user ?= @request.auth
```
...
```
@request.auth.collectionName = 'admins' ||
(
@request.auth.collectionName = 'users' &&
@collection.courseRegistrations.user ?= @request.auth.id &&
// make sure that the correct field name is used
@collection.courseRegistration.courseGroups ?= id
)
```
...
The manual join approach using @collection.* fields resolves the issue perfectly.
I appreciate you taking the time to reproduce the scenario with a test setup and providing this practical workaround.

# Complicated API rule · pocketbase pocketbase · Discussion #3805
created: 2023-11-21, last updated: 2026-04-16, [Read more](https://github.com/pocketbase/pocketbase/discussions/3805)

While we can perform a JOIN with the `@collection.*` rule, at the moment the filter rules doesn't support collection aliases and you can join the collection only once.
...
```
...
from courseRegistrations
```
And then the `users` List API rule could look something like:
```
@request.auth.id != "" &&
@collection.courseRegistrations.user ?= @request.auth.id &&
@collection.courseRegistrationsView.user ?= id
@collection.courseRegistrations.courseGroup ?= @collection.courseRegistrationsView.courseGroup
```
...
Just an example how the above rule could look if we decide to use `@collection.someCollection:someAlias.*` syntax with the next release:
```
@request.auth.id != "" &&
@collection.courseRegistrations.user ?= id &&
@collection.courseRegistrations:auth.user ?= @request.auth.id &&
@collection.courseRegistrations.courseGroup ?= @collection.courseRegistrations:auth.courseGroup
```
...
Eventually once we add support for back-relation references in the filters this can also look something like:
```
@request.auth.id != "" &&
courseRegistrations(user).courseGroup ?= @request.auth.courseRegistrations(user).courseGroup
```

